"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Judges chapters 20–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-judges-20-21.py

Ch20: Civil war against Benjamin — assembly at Mizpah, three battles,
      Phinehas interceding, YHWH's delayed victory, Gibeah destroyed (48 verses)
Ch21: Oath crisis — Jabesh-Gilead destroyed, Shiloh virgins seized,
      closing refrain (25 verses)

Christological focus:
- Ch20: Communal assembly for covenant justice; Phinehas as high-priestly type of
  Christ's intercession; YHWH's pedagogy of defeat before victory; purging evil
  as covenant holiness enacted; remnant preservation
- Ch21: Oath entanglement and its cost; YHWH's providential preservation of a
  broken covenant community; closing refrain as the book's cry for the true King
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>All Israel assembles at Mizpah <strong>as one man</strong> (<em>kəʾîš ʾeḥāḏ</em>) — the covenant community's unanimous solidarity in response to moral catastrophe. The NT counterpart is the apostolic gathering: 'All these with one accord were devoting themselves to prayer' (Acts 1:14) — the same formula of unanimous solidarity applied to the church in its foundational crisis before Pentecost. The assembly that gathers to enact covenant justice over a crime against one of its members is the prototype of the church's disciplinary gathering (Matt 18:17-20: 'where two or three are gathered in my name, I am there among them').</p>",
    "2": "<p>The <strong>chief men of all the people</strong> present themselves in the assembly of the people of God (<em>qəhal ʿam hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) — the full national assembly before YHWH. <em>qāhāl</em> (H6951, assembly/congregation) is the OT word from which NT <em>ekklēsia</em> (ἐκκλησία, assembly/church) draws both vocabulary and covenantal logic. The Septuagint translates <em>qāhāl</em> as <em>ekklēsia</em> throughout; Paul's use of <em>ekklēsia</em> for the NT community of believers consciously invokes this gathered assembly before God. The eschatological version is Hebrews 12:23: 'the assembly (<em>ekklēsiai</em>) of the firstborn who are enrolled in heaven.'</p>",
    "3": "<p>Benjamin hears of Israel's assembly — the news of the covenant community's gathering reaches those accused. The Levite speaks when asked 'how did this evil thing happen?' The gathering that calls the offending party to account is the covenant lawsuit (<em>rîb</em>) in action. Christ as eschatological judge gathers all nations before him (Matt 25:31-32: 'all the nations will be gathered before him, and he will separate people one from another'). The Mizpah assembly is a microcosm of the final judgment-assembly: all must give account.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Levite's testimony — his account of Gibeah as a witness before the assembly. Testimony (<em>ʿēḏût</em>) before the covenant assembly is required for judgment to proceed justly (Deut 17:6: 'on the evidence of two witnesses or three witnesses the one who is to die shall be put to death'). The assembly's role as witness, judge, and executor of covenant justice prefigures the church's judicial function (1 Cor 6:2-3: 'do you not know that the saints will judge the world?'). Christ himself is the faithful witness (<em>martys pistos</em>, Rev 1:5) who testifies truly before the Father.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Levite describes the men of Gibeah surrounding the house intending to kill him and abusing his concubine to death — the Sodom-pattern crime. The connection between Gibeah and Sodom is deliberate: Genesis 19's assault on angels becomes Judges 19's assault on a Levite. The escalation from Sodom to Gibeah is the book's theological descent: Israel has become Sodom. Jesus makes the same comparison in reverse: 'It will be more bearable on the day of judgment for the land of Sodom and Gomorrah than for that town' that rejects the gospel (Matt 10:15) — covenant privilege increases covenant responsibility.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Levite's act of cutting his concubine into twelve pieces and sending her throughout Israel — the twelve-part division invoking the twelve-tribe covenant structure. The concubine's divided body sent to the twelve tribes is an image of the covenant community's dismemberment: when covenant law is violated at this depth, the body politic itself is torn. Christ's body broken for many (Luke 22:19: 'This is my body, which is given for you') is the ultimate body-breaking — but unlike the concubine's death, Christ's breaking is voluntary and restorative rather than a symptom of covenant failure.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Levite's call: <strong>'Here you are, all people of Israel; give your advice and counsel here'</strong> — the call to corporate deliberation. The covenant community is the proper forum for justice when individual remedies have failed. The assembly's deliberation reflects the principle of communal wisdom: 'Where there is no guidance, a people falls, but in an abundance of counselors there is safety' (Prov 11:14). Christ sends his disciples with authority to bind and loose (Matt 18:18) — the church exercises delegated covenant authority in its communal discernment, not autonomous judgment.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The unanimous decision: <strong>none shall go home until Gibeah is judged</strong> — the total commitment of the covenant community to covenant justice. The communal vow to see justice through is echoed in Paul's description of the church's mutual accountability: 'if one member suffers, all suffer together; if one member is honored, all rejoice together' (1 Cor 12:26). The assembly's commitment to remain until justice is done reflects the eschatological patience of those who await the Son of God who 'will judge the living and the dead' (2 Tim 4:1) — justice will be accomplished.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The lot-casting to determine provisioning — the use of the sacred lot to organize the community's response. The <em>gôrāl</em> (H1486, lot) as a decision mechanism under YHWH's sovereign guidance reflects the theology that the disposal of the lot belongs to YHWH (Prov 16:33). The NT use of lots appears only once (Acts 1:26 — to select Matthias), after which the Spirit's direct guidance replaces the lot. Christ's seamless robe was cast for by lot (John 19:24), fulfilling Ps 22:18 — the last use of the lot for YHWH's disposal is against the One who replaced all other lots.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The precise proportional levy — one in ten provisions the army — and the clear declaration of purpose: to repay Gibeah according to 'all the outrage it committed in Israel.' The proportional covenant justice (exact repayment for what was done) applies the lex talionis principle at the national level. Christ absorbs the lex talionis at the cross: the exact repayment for human sin is borne by the sinless one, so that the sinners might receive his righteousness (2 Cor 5:21). The 'outrage' (<em>nəbālāh</em> H5039) in Israel is dealt with either through human justice or divine substitution.</p>",
    "11": "<p>All Israel unites against Gibeah <strong>as one man, as allies</strong> (<em>ḥăḇērîm</em> H2270). The covenant solidarity of the entire nation against a single city's crime demonstrates that covenant justice is communal, not merely legal. The NT counterpart is the church's unified judgment on serious sin (1 Cor 5:4-5: 'when you are assembled in the name of the Lord Jesus... you are to deliver this man to Satan'). The communal assembly for covenant discipline is not the church acting against a member but the community protecting its integrity — the same logic as Israel at Mizpah.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The formal demand sent throughout Benjamin — the ultimatum before attack. The covenant demand for the guilty party's surrender before military action is the principle of <em>ḥerem</em>-war: justice is offered before force is applied (Deut 20:10-11: 'when you draw near to a city to fight... first offer terms of peace'). Christ's ministry is the ultimate offer of peace before judgment: 'For God did not send his Son into the world to condemn the world, but in order that the world might be saved through him' (John 3:17). The offer precedes the judgment; rejection of the offer brings the judgment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The demand to <strong>deliver up the worthless fellows</strong> (<em>bənê-bəliyyaʿal</em>) — the Deuteronomic purge formula. Paul applies this formula directly to the NT church: 'Purge the evil person from among you' (1 Cor 5:13, quoting Deut 17:7). The apostolic citation of the Deuteronomic <em>bāʿar</em>-formula means the church inherits Israel's covenant obligation to maintain the covenant community's holiness by not tolerating covenant violation among its members. Benjamin's refusal to hand over the guilty — choosing tribal solidarity over covenant justice — is the failure that triggers the war.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Benjamin <strong>musters to fight</strong> — choosing solidarity with Gibeah over covenant justice. The tribe that would shelter the guilty rather than surrender them to justice has made the perpetrators' cause their own. This is the anti-pattern of the NT principle: 'Do not be unequally yoked with unbelievers. For what partnership has righteousness with lawlessness? Or what fellowship has light with darkness?' (2 Cor 6:14). Benjamin's alliance with Gibeah is the tribal equivalent of covenant compromise — preferring kinship bonds over covenant obligations. The cost is catastrophic.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Benjamin musters 26,700 swordsmen against Israel's 400,000. The numerical asymmetry is enormous — yet Benjamin wins the first two days. The theological principle: numbers do not determine covenant outcomes. This is the anti-Gideon scenario: YHWH gave victory to 300 against a vast horde; here he withholds victory from 400,000 against a small tribe. The pattern of YHWH's freedom to grant victory to the few or withhold it from the many is Paul's theological foundation: 'God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong' (1 Cor 1:27) — YHWH's power, not human calculation, determines outcomes.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The 700 left-handed Benjaminite slingers who 'could sling a stone at a hair and not miss' — elite specialized warriors. Their left-handedness echoes Ehud (Judg 3:15), Benjamin's most celebrated son. The unexpected instrumentality — the left hand that Israel's culture associated with weakness becoming the weapon of lethal precision — is the pattern of how YHWH works. Christ the 'stone' (1 Pet 2:7: 'the stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone') is hurled at the nations not with conventional force but with the precise power of the gospel. The sling-stone that hits its mark is the word of the cross.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Israel's 400,000 against Benjamin's 26,700 — a fifteen-to-one advantage. Yet the first two battles go to Benjamin. The theological commentary this implicit: numerical superiority without YHWH's specific commissioning for a specific battle does not guarantee victory. The principle of holy war theology is that the army is never the real combatant — YHWH is. Christ's community is never stronger than the smallest it appears when YHWH is with it: 'I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it' (Matt 16:18) — the church's strength is not its numbers but its foundation.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Israel's first oracle consultation at Bethel — YHWH answers 'Judah shall go up first.' The designation of Judah as the leading tribe echoes the opening of the entire book (1:1-2). Judah is the messianic tribe (Gen 49:10: the scepter shall not depart from Judah until Shiloh comes). Judah's primacy in Judges' opening conquest and in the civil war consultation points forward to the Davidic dynasty that Judah will produce — and ultimately to the Lion of the tribe of Judah (Rev 5:5) who alone is worthy to open the seals of judgment.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Israel rises and goes up to Gibeah — the simple obedience to the oracle. The Israelite army's morning departure following a divine oracle is the pattern of covenant obedience: hear, rise, go. Jesus's disciples are called with the same formula: 'Follow me' — and they left everything and followed (Matt 4:20,22). The simplicity of obedience is not naiveté; it is trust in the one who gave the direction. The first day's battle will be lost despite perfect obedience — a lesson that obedience does not guarantee immediate favorable outcomes in every engagement.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Israel draws up for battle against Benjamin at Gibeah. The battle formation — Israel setting their battle line against Benjamin — is the formal engagement of covenant judgment. Battles drawn up between covenant brothers are the darkest form of covenant failure: this war should never have needed to happen. The NT principle of preferring peace and reconciliation over litigation (Matt 5:25; 1 Cor 6:1-8) traces back to this: the covenant community's resort to force against its own members is always a sign that earlier reconciliation opportunities were missed.</p>",
    "21": "<p>22,000 Israelites fall on the first day. The defeat is unexpected — they came with YHWH's command and Judah's leadership, yet lost badly. This is the first pedagogical defeat: YHWH allows defeat not because his people were disobedient but to teach them dependence. Jesus's prediction of Peter's denial despite Peter's confident boast (Matt 26:33-35) and Peter's actual fall serves the same function: the disciple who trusts his own strength must experience defeat before he can be built on the true Foundation. YHWH permits the first defeat to deepen the assembly's prayer.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Israel encourages themselves and resumes battle positions. The response to defeat is not retreat or questioning the original mission, but renewed courage and commitment. <em>wayyitḥazzēq</em> (they strengthened themselves) — the same verb as Joshua 1:6-9's sevenfold call to 'be strong and courageous.' Courage after defeat is rarer and more genuine than courage before battle. The NT parallel is the disciples after the crucifixion: the apparent defeat of the cross is followed by the resurrection's restoration of courage and mission (John 20:19-21: 'Peace be with you. As the Father has sent me, even so I am sending you').</p>",
    "23": "<p>The second consultation: weeping before YHWH until evening, asking whether to continue. The combination of weeping and seeking divine guidance is the pattern of authentic lament (Ps 22:1-2: 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me? Why are you so far from saving me?'). YHWH's answer — 'go up against them' — repeats the first command with no added promise. The repetition without augmentation tests whether Israel will trust YHWH's word when it has twice been followed by defeat. Faith that persists despite apparent failure is the faith that inherits the promise (Heb 11:33-35: 'through faith conquered kingdoms... received back their dead by resurrection').</p>",
    "24": "<p>The second day's advance — Israel returns to fight despite the previous day's losses. Persistence in covenant-commissioned action despite setback is the character quality that YHWH is forming. The disciples' pattern of failure-and-return reflects the same formation: Peter denied three times and returned three times (John 21:15-17). The three-day battle structure echoes the three-day pattern of divine action throughout Scripture — three days before Sinai (Exod 19:11), Jonah's three days, and preeminently Christ's three days in the tomb. The third day brings the full victory that the first two could not.</p>",
    "25": "<p>18,000 more Israelites fall on the second day — all drawn-sword men, experienced warriors. The cumulative loss (40,000 total) is a profound humiliation. The theological function of the two defeats is now clear: YHWH is teaching that the covenant community cannot accomplish covenant justice through its own military power, no matter how great its numbers or righteous its cause. The disciples' parallel is Gethsemane: all of them fled (Matt 26:56). Before the resurrection's victory, all human power collapses. The community that seeks justice must first learn that it cannot achieve it by its own strength.</p>",
    "26": "<p>All Israel goes to Bethel for full penitential worship: weeping, fasting, burnt offerings, peace offerings. The triple action corresponds to three dimensions of return to YHWH: weeping (contrition), fasting (self-denial/humility), sacrifice (covenant restoration). Joel's call uses the same triple pattern: 'return to me with all your heart, with fasting, with weeping, and with mourning' (Joel 2:12). The church's penitential practices — fasting, prayer, confession — trace back to this pattern of corporate return to YHWH after failure. The burnt offering (total devotion) and peace offering (covenant fellowship) together express the complete restoration of the Israel-YHWH relationship.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The ark of the covenant of God is at Bethel, and <strong>Phinehas son of Eleazar son of Aaron</strong> ministers before it. Phinehas is the great high-priestly type of intercessory ministry: his zeal at Baal-Peor 'made atonement for the people of Israel' (Num 25:13; Ps 106:30-31). Here he intercedes before the ark as the nation's representative. The high priest's ministry before the ark of the covenant typifies Christ's high-priestly intercession before the Father: 'He always lives to make intercession for them' (Heb 7:25). Phinehas's intercession at the critical moment — before the decisive third battle — corresponds to Christ's intercession that ensures the final victory.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Phinehas asks: shall we fight again or cease? YHWH's unambiguous answer: <strong>'Go up, for tomorrow I will give them into your hand.'</strong> The explicit divine promise of victory — which was absent in the first two oracles — comes only after Israel has gone through the full penitential process. The sequence is theologically exact: presumptuous confidence (days 1-2) → defeat → genuine repentance → divine promise. This is the resurrection pattern: the disciples' confidence is destroyed by the cross → genuine grief and repentance → the Father's promise of victory through the resurrection. Christ's 'tomorrow I will give them into your hand' is Easter morning.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Israel sets an <strong>ambush around Gibeah</strong> — the strategy that echoes Joshua's Ai campaign (Josh 8:2-22). YHWH had commanded Joshua to set an ambush at Ai; here the same strategy is employed against a Canaanized Israelite city. The deliberate tactical echo frames Gibeah as a Canaanite stronghold that must be taken by the same method as Ai: feigned retreat, ambush, fire. The pattern of apparent retreat concealing a decisive strike is the cross's logic: the apparent defeat of Good Friday conceals the decisive strike of Easter. The withdrawal that looks like defeat is the setup for the ambush of resurrection.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The third day's deployment — Israel takes position as before, presenting the same feigned vulnerability. The identical formation on the third day requires the most trust from the army: having lost on the first and second days with this same formation, they must deploy again without knowing that today will be different. This is the faith asked of the disciples between the cross and the resurrection: the same vulnerability, the same apparent hopelessness, but holding the promise that 'on the third day he will rise' (Luke 18:33). The third deployment is the deployment of faith.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Benjamin is drawn out and begins to strike down Israelites 'as at other times' — the deception is working. The initial casualties on the third day are intentional: they are the price of making the feigned retreat convincing. The willingness to accept casualties to achieve the larger victory is the logic of Christ's passion: 'Unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit' (John 12:24). The apparent defeat that enables the decisive victory requires genuine cost, not merely the appearance of loss.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Benjamin's false confidence: 'They are routed before us as before' — the victory assumption that makes the deception complete. False confidence based on past success is what blinds Benjamin to the changed situation. The religious establishment's false confidence that they have dealt with Jesus ('He is dead; the tomb is sealed') mirrors this: past 'victories' (silencing the prophets, killing James) created the assumption that resurrection was impossible. YHWH's reversal exposes false confidence in exactly the moment it is most certain of itself.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The main Israelite force turns and fights at Baal-tamar while the ambush forces rush from their position. The simultaneous two-pronged assault represents the coordinated divine and human action in covenant warfare: YHWH's power (the ambush he commanded) and Israel's obedience (the main force's turn). This is the pattern of 'work out your own salvation with fear and trembling, for it is God who works in you' (Phil 2:12-13) — divine and human action are simultaneous and inseparable. The turn-and-fight on the third day is the resurrection response to the cross: the humiliated turns to face the opposition.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Ten thousand chosen men of Israel assault Gibeah — and <strong>they did not know that disaster was close</strong> (regarding the Benjaminites). The phrase 'did not know that disaster was close' is a direct echo of 16:20's 'he did not know that YHWH had left him' — Samson's blindness to the departure of YHWH's presence. The Benjaminites who sheltered the perpetrators of Gibeah are now in the position of Samson: they do not know that the moment of YHWH's decisive judgment has arrived. The sudden reversal from apparent triumph to realized disaster is the pattern of YHWH's judgments throughout Scripture.</p>",
    "35": "<p><strong>YHWH defeated Benjamin before Israel</strong> — the divine action is given theological priority before the tactical account. The sequence (divine verdict → tactical explanation) is the standard Deuteronomistic formula for judge-era battles: YHWH acts, Israel executes his action. 25,100 Benjaminites fall — over 93% of their force in a single day. This is the same proportion as Israel's two-day loss (40,000 of 400,000 = 10%) reversed and multiplied: YHWH's judgment when it comes is total and swift. The cross works the same reversal: death absorbed in one day destroys death's dominion permanently.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The Israelites 'gave ground to Benjamin because they trusted the ambush.' The feigned retreat as strategy requires trust in the commander's overall plan, not confidence in the immediate tactical situation. This is the definition of faith: acting on the basis of the commander's promise rather than the immediate sensory evidence. 'Faith is the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen' (Heb 11:1) — the retreating army was acting on YHWH's promise, not on their own strength or the apparent tactical situation. The third day required the same faith as the first two days, but this time the promise had been explicitly given.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The ambush forces rush Gibeah and put the city to the sword. The simultaneous action on multiple fronts — the main force turning, the ambush attacking the city — is the coordinated victory that the three-day process produced. The military coordination typifies the cosmic coordination of the cross and resurrection: the Father's plan, the Son's obedience, and the Spirit's power operating simultaneously in a single decisive event. No single moment or single actor can claim the victory; the whole plan works as a unity.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The smoke signal from Gibeah — the pre-arranged sign that coordinates the final phase of battle. The signal that coordinates the final victory is a communication system between the ambush forces and the main army. Christ sends the Holy Spirit as the coordinating presence for the church's mission: 'I will send you the Helper' (John 16:7). The Spirit is the smoke-signal of the resurrection — the visible, dramatic sign that the decisive victory has been achieved and that the church can now turn from retreat to advance.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The main Israelite force turns in battle when it sees the smoke — the signal enables the reversal of direction. The force that had been retreating now advances against the pursuers. The reversal of direction — from flight to pursuit — is the resurrection pattern for the disciples: the scattered, fleeing disciples of Good Friday become the fearless witnesses of Acts 2. The same people, the same cause, but with the decisive victory signal (the resurrection and Pentecost) now in hand. 'You will receive power when the Holy Spirit has come upon you, and you will be my witnesses' (Acts 1:8).</p>",
    "40": "<p>The smoke pillar rises from Gibeah to the sky — the city going up in fire. Gibeah's destruction by fire — the Sodom-equivalent punishment for Sodom-equivalent sin — is the complete execution of covenant justice. The fire that consumes the city that harbored the sons of Belial cleanses the land of the pollution that their crime had created. Christ's purifying judgment is described in similar terms: 'his winnowing fork is in his hand, and he will clear his threshing floor and gather his wheat into the barn, but the chaff he will burn with unquenchable fire' (Matt 3:12). Fire purifies what it consumes.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Benjamin sees that disaster has struck them. The moment of recognition — when the fog of false confidence lifts and the reality of YHWH's judgment becomes visible — is the pattern of every eschatological recognition scene in the NT. 'Every eye will see him, even those who pierced him, and all tribes of the earth will wail on account of him' (Rev 1:7). The Benjaminites' terror on seeing that YHWH's hand is against them corresponds to the terror of the final recognition that what was dismissed has proven to be real. Judgment is not avoidable; it is only delayed.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Benjamin flees toward the wilderness road as Israel pursues, and men from the cities cut them off. The encirclement of a fleeing army — trapped between a pursuing force and a cutting-off force — is the completion of the ambush strategy. There is no escape route. The eschatological judgment has the same completeness: 'where can I go from your Spirit? Or where can I flee from your presence? If I ascend to heaven, you are there! If I make my bed in Sheol, you are there!' (Ps 139:7-8). There is nowhere to flee from YHWH's judgment — except into his mercy, which the 600 remnant at Rimmon will implicitly seek.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Israel encircles and pursues Benjamin, easily overtaking them at Gibeah on the east. The ease of the final pursuit — 'easily trodden down' (<em>hirḏîpûhû mənûḥāh</em>) — contrasts with the two days of costly defeat. The victory YHWH grants when he is working is effortless compared to the struggle when he withholds. 'He gives to his beloved sleep' (Ps 127:2) — YHWH's victories do not require Israel's exhaustion when he is the primary actor. The hard labor of two defeated days is replaced by the effortless pursuit of the third day when YHWH's hand is extended.</p>",
    "44": "<p>18,000 Benjaminites fall in the first phase of the rout — matching Israel's second-day casualty count exactly. The numerical symmetry is YHWH's covenant justice expressed arithmetically: the 18,000 who fell among the Israelites (v25) are answered by 18,000 fallen Benjaminites. This is not coincidence but theological patterning: the narrator wants the reader to see the balance of covenant justice. Christ absorbed the perfect weight of human sin to restore the perfect balance of divine justice — 'one act of righteousness leads to justification and life for all men' (Rom 5:18), answering the one act of trespass that brought condemnation.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The remaining Benjaminites flee to the rock of Rimmon — 600 survivors reaching a natural fortress. <strong>Rimmon</strong> (<em>rimmôn</em> H7417) means 'pomegranate' — the fruit with many seeds, a symbol of fruitfulness and blessing in Israel (Num 13:23; Song 4:3). The 600 survivors at the rock of the pomegranate are the seed-remnant from which Benjamin will be restored. YHWH always preserves a remnant: 'Is it not yet a very little while until Lebanon shall be turned into a fruitful field?' (Isa 29:17). The remnant at Rimmon is the seed of Benjamin's future, preserved precisely at the rock of fruitfulness.</p>",
    "46": "<p>25,000 Benjaminites fall — drawn-sword men, all warriors. The near-total destruction of Benjamin's military capacity is the fulfillment of Jotham's fire-curse on the opposite side of the Abimelech narrative (9:20): the fire of covenant judgment consumes those who shelter covenant violation. The remnant of 600 (v47) from a tribe of over 26,000 is a 97% loss — catastrophic, but not total. Paul's theology of the remnant applies: 'So too at the present time there is a remnant, chosen by grace' (Rom 11:5). Even in the most severe covenant judgment, YHWH preserves his remnant by grace.</p>",
    "47": "<p><strong>600 men</strong> flee to the rock of Rimmon and stay there four months. Six hundred is the number of Gideon's stripped-down force at its initial maximum (before the reduction to 300) and the number of Abimelech's hired men (9:4) — it is a functional military unit. Four months at Rimmon creates the crisis that ch21 addresses: enough men survive to rebuild the tribe, but not enough women remain to do it. The four months of waiting at the rock of Rimmon is the period between death and restoration — the 'three days' extended. YHWH preserves a remnant through the crisis so that restoration becomes possible.</p>",
    "48": "<p>Israel burns all of Benjamin's cities. The total destruction — men, animals, cities — is the full application of the <em>ḥērem</em> (ban) to an Israelite city that had become Canaanite. Deuteronomy 13:12-17 prescribes this exact judgment for an Israelite city that embraced <em>bəliyyaʿal</em> ('worthlessness/Belial'): burn it completely with all its spoil. The fires of Gibeah, then Benjamin's cities, complete the application of the ban to Israel's own territory. The purifying judgment that was supposed to fall on Canaan falls instead on Israel — because Israel has become Canaan. The NT warning: 'if anyone destroys God's temple, God will destroy him' (1 Cor 3:17).</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>The oath at Mizpah — Israel swore <strong>no man shall give his daughter to Benjamin as a wife</strong>. The oath that was meant to punish Benjamin now becomes the obstacle to Benjamin's restoration. Rash oaths that create unintended consequences are a recurring biblical warning (Jephthah's daughter in ch11; Saul's oath in 1 Sam 14:24-30). The NT principle: 'let what you say be simply yes or no; anything more than this comes from evil' (Matt 5:37). The elaborate oath-machinery that Israel has constructed creates more problems than it solves, and the solutions the assembly devises are worse than the original oath.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The people weep before God and lament: <strong>Why, O Lord, has this happened in Israel, that today one tribe should be lacking?</strong> The lament before God in the face of self-caused disaster — weeping over consequences that their own decisions produced — is a theologically complex moment. They are asking YHWH 'why?' about a situation created by their own actions. YHWH's response is implicit in the chapter's resolution: he does not answer the 'why' but provides the means of restoration. The divine pastoral response to lament is often not explanation but provision — 'he heals the brokenhearted and binds up their wounds' (Ps 147:3).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The lament over the missing tribe: <strong>'Why has this happened that one tribe should be lacking from Israel?'</strong> The twelve-tribe structure is a covenant given, not a demographic accident — its disruption is felt as a theological wound. The Twelve Apostles of Jesus deliberately correspond to the twelve tribes: 'You who have followed me will also sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel' (Matt 19:28). The reconstitution of the twelve in Jesus's mission (choosing twelve) and the reconstitution after Judas's defection (Acts 1:26) reflects the same theological conviction that YHWH's covenant community must be complete.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Israel builds an altar and offers burnt and peace offerings at Bethel — the same sacrifice as before the third battle (20:26). Sacrifice at the beginning and end of the civil war narrative frames the whole episode within Israel's worship-life: however catastrophic the moral collapse, Israel remains the covenant community that offers to YHWH. The sacrifices' persistence amid the chaos of civil war, oath-crisis, and demographic catastrophe is a sign that the covenant itself has not been severed. Christ's high-priestly offering, made once for all (Heb 10:10), is the sacrifice that guarantees the covenant's permanence regardless of the covenant people's failures.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The second oath: death to any tribe that did not come to Mizpah. The second oath is discovered when the assembly realizes it might solve their wife-shortage problem: Jabesh-Gilead's absence creates both a justification for attacking them and a source of virgin wives for Benjamin. The entanglement of oath with pragmatic solution is characteristic of human attempts to manage crisis without divine direction. When Christ says 'do not swear at all' (Matt 5:34), he is pointing to exactly this pattern: binding oaths generate binding consequences that entangle the community in morally compromised solutions.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Israel has <strong>compassion on Benjamin</strong> because 'YHWH has made a breach in the tribes of Israel.' The attribution of Benjamin's near-destruction to YHWH is the theological interpretation: the outcome was YHWH's judicial act, not merely Israel's military excess. The divine compassion that Israel now feels toward Benjamin mirrors YHWH's own character: 'As a father shows compassion to his children, so YHWH shows compassion to those who fear him' (Ps 103:13). The grief over a lost brother is the human echo of the divine grief over lost sinners — 'there is joy before the angels of God over one sinner who repents' (Luke 15:10).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The oath problem stated explicitly: <strong>how shall we provide wives for those who are left, since we have sworn by YHWH?</strong> The community is caught between two legitimate obligations — covenant oath and covenant solidarity with a surviving tribe — with no clean solution. The NT does not escape the messiness of covenant community in a broken world; it provides the principle for navigating it: love (not rule-following) as the supreme criterion (1 Cor 13:13; Matt 22:36-40). The greatest commandment framework prioritizes the love that restores over the legal technicality that destroys.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The discovery of Jabesh-Gilead's absence from the Mizpah muster. Jabesh-Gilead's absence creates the means for solving the wife-crisis — but at the cost of destroying another Israelite community. The 'solution' is disproportionate: an entire city is destroyed to provide wives for 400 of 600 surviving Benjaminites. Every solution the assembly devises is ethically compromised because the root problem — the rash oath — cannot be honestly undone. Christ does not provide morally compromised solutions to covenant problems; he dissolves the underlying problem through forgiveness and new creation: 'Behold, I am making all things new' (Rev 21:5).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The census confirms Jabesh-Gilead's complete absence. The census mechanism — the community able to identify exactly who was and was not present — reflects the covenant community's accountability structure. Every member is known and their presence or absence is noted. The NT counterpart is the church's pastoral care: the good shepherd leaves the ninety-nine to find the one lost sheep (Luke 15:4). The census that identifies Jabesh-Gilead's absence serves Israel's punitive purposes; the census of YHWH's 'sheep' serves his redemptive ones.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Twelve thousand warriors sent to Jabesh-Gilead — the community dispatches military force to execute the oath's death penalty against an absent tribe. The irony is severe: the community that just finished a war to execute justice on Gibeah now conducts another war on an Israelite city to solve the wife-crisis. One solution requires another violent action, which will require another solution, in a cascade of consequences from the original rash oath. Jesus breaks this cascade: 'You have heard that it was said... but I say to you' (Matt 5:21ff.) — the kingdom ethic offers a way out of the escalating cycle of obligation-and-consequence.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The specific instruction: kill every male and non-virgin female, spare virgins. The sexual-purity criterion for sparing life is a perversion of covenant holiness: the women of Jabesh-Gilead are categorized as property rather than persons, their value determined entirely by their marital status. The NT principle of the equal dignity of all persons in Christ — 'there is neither male nor female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus' (Gal 3:28) — is the redemptive answer to the dehumanization that covenant failure produces. The women of Jabesh-Gilead, treated as objects, foreshadow Mary Magdalene and the women disciples whom Christ treats as witnesses and participants.</p>",
    "12": "<p>400 virgin girls are found and brought to Shiloh. The number 400 — leaving 200 Benjaminite men without wives — is a providential detail: it ensures the problem is partially but not fully solved by Jabesh-Gilead alone, necessitating the Shiloh plan. The incompleteness of the Jabesh solution drives the second solution, which is worse. The partial solutions that human ingenuity devises in a crisis of covenant failure always leave a remainder — only YHWH's complete solution addresses the whole problem. 'He who calls you is faithful; he will surely do it' (1 Thess 5:24) — YHWH's solutions are complete.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The peace offer to Benjamin at Rimmon — the formal end of hostilities. After the destruction of near-totality, Israel reaches out to the remnant with <em>šālôm</em>. The pattern of destruction followed by peace-offer is the gospel pattern in extreme negative form: the community that has destroyed Benjamin now offers restoration. But it is an offer contingent on their own ability to solve the wife-problem — the peace offer comes bundled with a pragmatic solution. Christ's peace offer is unconditional: 'Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you. Not as the world gives do I give to you' (John 14:27) — the gift is not contingent on the recipient's ability to complete the transaction.</p>",
    "14": "<p>400 wives from Jabesh-Gilead given to Benjamin — but 200 men remain without wives. The partial solution leaves 200 men without spouses and the community still needing to find a way around its oath. The 200 who remain unprovided-for represent the persistent incompleteness of human attempts to repair covenant damage. YHWH's redemptive purposes always provision the full number: 'Not one of all the good promises that YHWH had made to the house of Israel had failed; all came to pass' (Josh 21:45). Human solutions leave remainders; YHWH's solution leaves none.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>The people had compassion on Benjamin because YHWH had made a breach</strong> (<em>pereṣ</em> H6556) in the tribes of Israel. The compassion that sees YHWH's hand in the crisis — not blaming Benjamin alone or themselves alone but recognizing divine judgment as the immediate cause — is a moment of theological clarity. The NT applies the same logic to human suffering: 'For the Lord disciplines the one he loves, and chastises every son whom he receives' (Heb 12:6, quoting Prov 3:11-12). Seeing YHWH's hand in discipline does not remove the pain but changes its meaning: it is covenant discipline toward restoration, not abandonment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The elders seek how to provide wives for the remaining 200 — taking up the remaining pastoral problem. The elders' responsibility to ensure the tribe's future is a form of covenant care for the community's weakest members. The pastoral concern for the remnant that cannot provide for itself is the OT background for the NT elder's role: 'Shepherd the flock of God that is among you' (1 Pet 5:2). The elders who solve the Benjamin problem inadequately are doing the right thing (caring for the remnant) with the wrong tools (rash oaths and violent expedients).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The declaration: <strong>there must be an inheritance for the survivors of Benjamin</strong> (<em>yərūšat pəlêṭāh ləḇinyāmîn</em>). <em>yərūšāh</em> (H3425, inheritance) — the covenant term for the tribal allotment. The insistence that the survivors must have an inheritance is a declaration that YHWH's covenant grant of land and lineage to Benjamin cannot simply be forfeited through one generation's catastrophe. This is the logic of the resurrection: even death cannot permanently annul YHWH's covenant promises. 'The gifts and calling of God are irrevocable' (Rom 11:29) — the remnant inherits the promise of the whole.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The oath's binding force: <strong>we cannot give them wives from our daughters</strong>. The recognition of an oath's binding force — even when its consequences are destructive — reflects the covenantal seriousness with which Israel treats sworn words. Jephthah's daughter died because of the same principle (11:35-36). Jesus's word about oaths (Matt 5:37) is not a dismissal of promises but a call to the kind of truthfulness that makes elaborate oath-machinery unnecessary. When 'yes' always means 'yes,' the crisis of binding oaths that produce inescapable consequences does not arise.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Shiloh festival plan — using the annual feast of YHWH to circumvent the oath by technical means. The annual feast at Shiloh involves dancing daughters; if Benjamin 'seizes' them rather than receiving them as gifts, the oath technically is not violated (no one 'gave'). The casuistic reasoning — following the letter while violating the spirit — is the NT's prime target in its critique of Pharisaic law-keeping (Matt 23:23: 'you tithe mint and dill and cumin and have neglected the weightier matters of the law: justice and mercy and faithfulness'). Technical compliance with the oath while facilitating what the oath was meant to prevent is the most transparent form of covenant bad faith.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The instruction to Benjamin: lie in wait in the vineyards and seize the daughters of Shiloh. The ambush vocabulary — <em>ʾāraḇ</em> (H693, to lie in wait) — used in a religious festival context is deeply disturbing. The military ambush tactic that was used against Gibeah and Benjamin is now recommended for use at a worship festival to obtain wives. The sacrilege of using holy-time and holy-place for morally compromised purposes is the antithesis of the sanctified worship YHWH requires. Christ's cleansing of the temple (John 2:13-16) is the direct confrontation with the same contamination: using sacred space for pragmatic purposes that violate its holiness.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Benjamin seizes wives from the dancers at Shiloh. The daughters of Shiloh celebrating YHWH's feast become the victims of a pre-planned ambush during worship. The violation of sacred time and space through violence against women is the book's final horror — worse in some ways than Gibeah, because it happens at the central sanctuary with community sanction. The contamination of worship with violence and coercion is what Amos condemns (Amos 5:21-24: 'I hate, I despise your feasts...let justice roll down like waters'). The true feast of YHWH is one from which no one is taken against their will; it is an invitation to which all are freely welcomed (Rev 19:9: 'Blessed are those who are invited to the marriage supper of the Lamb').</p>",
    "22": "<p>The anticipated complaint-management: tell the fathers 'grant them graciously to us, because we did not take a wife in battle, and you did not give them to us.' The elaborate legal justification — you are not oath-breakers because you did not 'give' them — is morally transparent self-deception. The community that prides itself on keeping its oath has arranged for its violation in everything but technical form. Paul's critique of similar reasoning is direct: 'Their condemnation is just' (Rom 3:8) — the argument that doing evil might produce good does not remove the condemnation of the evil done.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Benjamin takes wives and returns to their inheritance — rebuilds their cities and dwells in them. The restoration of Benjamin to their tribal territory and the rebuilding of their cities is YHWH's providential preservation of the covenant structure despite every human attempt to either destroy it (the war) or compromise it (the wife-seizure). YHWH's covenant purposes survive both human sin and human repentance — even deeply flawed repentance that produces further sin. The rebuilt cities of Benjamin will produce Saul, Jonathan, and Paul — YHWH's purposes run through the broken vessel of Benjamin's restoration.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Israel disperses to their tribal territories — the covenant community reconstitutes in its proper distributed form. The dispersal to 'tribe and clan' is the return to the covenant structure of separate-but-united peoples under YHWH's governance. The book of Judges begins with the tribes each in their own territory (ch1) and ends the same way — but internally, everything has changed. The covenant community that entered the land under Joshua's unified leadership now exits Judges deeply fragmented, morally compromised, and desperately needing the king they will ask for in 1 Samuel. The structural answer — the monarchy — is waiting in the wings.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The closing verdict: <strong>In those days there was no king in Israel. Everyone did what was right in his own eyes.</strong> The book's final word is simultaneously a diagnosis, a lament, and a prayer. <em>Meleḵ</em> (H4428, king) — what Israel needs is not merely a better political system but a king after YHWH's own heart who will enforce the covenant from the inside rather than through legal compulsion. The entire book of Judges is the long argument for the Davidic king — and through David, for the messianic King. 'The LORD will be king over all the earth' (Zech 14:9); 'he will reign over the house of Jacob forever, and of his kingdom there will be no end' (Luke 1:33). In those days, there was no king. In the fullness of time, the King came.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'judges')
    merge_comm(c, CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'judges', c)
    print(f'judges mkt-christ: wrote {sum(len(v) for v in CHRIST.values())} verses across ch 20-21')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
